I'm posting this as a non-template issue, as I suspect this isn't a bug etc, it's just one of those "you probably never should have done it this way, so crying about it now isn't very compelling, but still, lots of people did do it this way so here's a note on it," things. 

I work on a portfolio of apps where I've seen this quite a bit:

@HostBinding(class.MyComponent) true;

It always had code smell to me, if felt like a potential no-op. But it worked as expected so that was that; leave it alone. 

Until Angular 11.2. Now that class does not get applied to the host. There's just nothing there, the element has no class. I roll back to 11.0.9, everything works, you see the class on the element in the inspector, etc. I update to 11.2, it breaks. 

This fixes it:

@HostBinding(class.MyComponent) get hostclass() { return 'true' };

(This is how the decorator is doc'd in Angular.io as well). 

I can kind of surmise why this might be the case, being as I was always suspicious of how it was being done originally. This is just a note that perhaps something needs to be made visible insofar as a change that makes reading and applying this information more strict, and maybe it'll save some poor soul out there a headache.

# üêû bug report

### Affected Package

Something related to Karma tests.


### Is this a regression?

Not sure, I found this issue first in Angular 11.2.1 and while making the repro I validated it also happens in version 11.0.9.

### Description

I found a case in which Angular swallows exceptions thrown from inside the `ngOnChanges` method when running inside of a test. But only if the exception is thrown inside of a `beforeEach`.

I have this code:
```typescript
@Component({ selector: `inner`, template: `` })
class InnerComponent {
  @Input() myInput: string;
  ngOnChanges() {
    throw "Some unhandled exception";
  }
}
@Component({ template: `<inner [myInput]="someVar"></inner>` })
class TestHostComponent {
  someVar = null;
}
...
describe("Some test", () => {
  beforeEach(fakeAsync(() => {
    fixture = TestBed.createComponent(TestHostComponent);
    fixture.autoDetectChanges();
  }));

  it("does stuff", fakeAsync(() => {
    tick();
  }));
});
```

You can see that the ngOnChanges throws an exception, which is being swallowed and instead I get this:
```
Chrome 88.0.4324.182 (Linux x86_64) Some test does stuff FAILED
        Error: 1 timer(s) still in the queue.
            at UserContext.<anonymous> (node_modules/zone.js/dist/zone-testing.js:1760:1)
            at ZoneDelegate.invoke (node_modules/zone.js/dist/zone-evergreen.js:364:1)
            at ProxyZoneSpec.push.QpwO.ProxyZoneSpec.onInvoke (node_modules/zone.js/dist/zone-testing.js:292:1)
            at ZoneDelegate.invoke (node_modules/zone.js/dist/zone-evergreen.js:363:1)
            at Zone.run (node_modules/zone.js/dist/zone-evergreen.js:123:1)
            at runInTestZone (node_modules/zone.js/dist/zone-testing.js:545:1)
            at UserContext.<anonymous> (node_modules/zone.js/dist/zone-testing.js:560:1)
            at <Jasmine>
```

If I move the `beforeEach` code to the `it`:
```typescript
  it("does stuff", fakeAsync(() => {
    fixture = TestBed.createComponent(TestHostComponent);
    fixture.autoDetectChanges();
    tick();
  }));
```

Then the exception is as expected:
```
Chrome 88.0.4324.182 (Linux x86_64) Some test does stuff FAILED
        Some unhandled exception thrown
```

This makes extremely difficult debugging tests, as the timer it refers to is not one created by our custom code but some internal code in Angular or Karma.

